    <h1>1&#xD;&#xA;STRETCH AT A YOGA CLASS</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201223/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-23"><time>2020-12-23</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>If you find your­self rush­ing through the day or lead­ing a fast-paced life­style, take a breather and join a yoga class.</p>
    <p>The age-old prac­tice from In­dia cre­ates a union between the body, mind and spirit by in­cor­po­rat­ing breath­ing ex­er­cises, med­i­ta­tion and poses de­signed to en­cour­age re­lax­ation and pro­mote mind­ful­ness. There are var­i­ous types of the prac­tice such as hatha yoga, yin yoga, vinyasa yoga and aerial yoga.</p>
    <p>Yoga in­struc­tor Danielle Ha­jar of Fit­ness, Whole­ness, Yoga, who teaches at var­i­ous stu­dios, said: “Yoga not only as­sists in flex­i­bil­ity and strength­ens the mus­cles, but also sharp­ens the mind and en­cour­ages you to tune in to your body and no­tice how you phys­i­cally feel in the mo­ment.”</p>
    <p>New­bies can fol­low videos on YouTube or sign up for classes at stu­dios such as Am­bi­ence Yoga and Real Yoga.</p>


